<article class="blog-post">

<li class="card general-content-card">
    <div class="tag">
        
    <p class="taxonomy-field">
        
        <a href="/magazine/themes/art-design">Art &amp; Design</a>, <a href="/magazine/themes/social-justice">Social Justice</a>, <a href="/magazine/themes/traditional-knowledge">Traditional Knowledge</a>
    </p>

    </div>
    <h1 class="title">
        <i>Good Medicine</i>: Meda DeWitt on Tlingit Art, Healing, and Reclamation<br />
        <span class="md-sans">
            

        </span>
    </h1>
    <div class="byline no-underline">
        November 14, 2023 |
<a href="/authors/francesca-du-brock">Francesca Du Brock</a>, <a href="/authors/meda-dewitt">Meda DeWitt</a> |         <a href="/magazine/good-medicine-meda-dewitt#disqus_thread">Comments</a>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
        <p>Since time immemorial, Indigenous  traditional healers have provided services for communities throughout the world.  In Alaska, traditional healing was the primary form of healthcare for Alaska  Native peoples until colonization. Customary medicine practices and many other  cultural traditions were disrupted during epidemics in the early 1900s of  smallpox, measles, flu, chicken pox, and influenza, collectively known as &ldquo;The  Great Death.&rdquo; These events, along with assimilation tactics of boarding schools  and Christian missions, severed children from parents, elders, and cultural  teachers—and, by extension, much of this traditional knowledge. </p> 
<p>The  U.S. government   destroyed traditional economies and resources, forcibly broke up families,  forbade the practice of Native language and culture, and made Indigenous  religious practices illegal. From the 1880s well into the twentieth century,  many Native children living in rural areas were forced to attend boardings  schools far removed from their communities,  in Alaska and across the  country. Colonial violence contributed to the erosion of  the health and wellness of Indigenous communities—on spiritual, physical, environmental,  and emotional levels. Today&rsquo;s traditional healers preserve and perpetuate vital  cultural knowledge, practicing at the confluence of ancient wisdom and the  pressures and rhythms of modern life. </p>
<p>Currently on view at the Anchorage  Museum, <em><a href="https://www.anchoragemuseum.org/exhibits/good-medicine/" target="_blank">Good  Medicine</a></em> is a yearlong exhibition focused on renewing relationships  with land, ancestors, and culture. It features the work  of Indigenous healers from across Alaska, affirming that, despite the past 300  years of colonization, the spirit of Alaska Native peoples survives. Artwork  displays change with each monthly moon cycle, and active  programming of the space invites healers to facilitate discussions, workshops,  story circles, and other forms of knowledge sharing and exchange.</p>
<p>In this interview, Anchorage Museum chief curator Francesca Du Brock speaks with Tlingit traditional healer and <em>Good  Medicine </em>curator <a href="https://medaforalaska.com/" target="_blank">Meda DeWitt</a> about her journey into healing work and her  inspirations for the exhibition.</p>
<figure>
    <img src="/images/blog/tlingit-blanket-bag-mukluks.jpg" alt="Three objects side by side on white background: a cloak-like blanket with red edges and central design on black. A red bag with long blue strap and animal design in blue, hanging from a wooden rack. A pair of booths with black furry fringe, pink blossom embroidery, and bright red cuffs." />
    <figcaption><div class="figcaption-inner">
            Left to right: Tlingit button blanket by Natalee Wigen, Tlingit octopus bag by Ruby Sobaleff, and Inupiat mukluks by Mary Sears. All three women are part of the Traditional Healing Clinic at the Southcentral Foundation. At the clinic, tribal doctors assist customer-owners of all ages using practices such as traditional medicine, counseling, physical therapy, and talking circles. 
            <div class="credit">
                Photos courtesy of the Anchorage Museum
            </div>
        </div></figcaption>
</figure>
<p><strong>What brought you to your work as  a traditional healer? </strong></p>
<p>My journey to this work is informed by  culture, by community, by elders, by my experiences, and by story. It&rsquo;s a holistic  web of knowledge that&rsquo;s intricately entwined. My learning began  very early with education on Prince of Wales Island in Klawock and Hollis. I  had a predisposition for plant medicine and intuitive gifts, and I spent a lot  of time running free outside. My family, and especially my grandparents,  fostered those healing abilities within me. </p>
<p>As an Indigenous  person, I struggled with assimilation and colonization. It was difficult in my  teens when I was forming my identity. Still, I learned how to make salve, continued  to pick berries, and began intuitive counseling and energy work. However, I  didn&rsquo;t take it very seriously. Then, when I was eighteen, my grandpa had a  vision and said that I would be doing this healing work as an adult and that I  needed to get back to it. I had no idea how to get to that point in his vision. </p>
<p>I grew up reading books my grandpa gave  me on home remedies, anatomy, physiology, and plant lore. So, I just started  reading. At that point, I didn&rsquo;t even know what questions to ask. I started  looking for a mentor, and I was told discouraging things like &ldquo;you&rsquo;re too old  to train&rdquo; or &ldquo;you&rsquo;re too white to be a traditional healer,&rdquo; because of my mixed  heritage. </p>
<p>Luckily, a short time later, my Tlingit grandmother moved in with me.  She told me family stories and solidified my identity as a human being in  relation to my ancestors, family, and worldview. It was empowering to realize  that I didn&rsquo;t need anybody else&rsquo;s permission to become a healer. I didn&rsquo;t need  to look for external validation of my own identity outside of my family,  community, and cultural group. I just had to be who I was supposed to be. And then the right mentors started to manifest with grace at the time  that they were needed. </p>
<p><strong>What similarities  do you see between artistic practice and traditional healing?</strong></p>
<p>Traditional healing is like art in  thought and spirit. Within Indigenous cultures, there is fluidity between these  realms of art and healing. Traditionally, art wasn&rsquo;t separate from every other  domain in life. It&rsquo;s Western culture that separates knowledge into different  categories. For example, it&rsquo;s very common for a medicine person to make their  own masks or rattles. I think that art is a medium for teaching and reaching  people at different levels of their being. It isn&rsquo;t linear—it&rsquo;s psychological,  mental, emotional, spiritual, and relational. It&rsquo;s holistic and ever-expanding.</p>
<p>When I work on a person&rsquo;s body, I  anticipate. I don&rsquo;t direct it. I don&rsquo;t force it. I don&rsquo;t make it. I don&rsquo;t have hard  expectations. I anticipate that the body will desire to be the best it can be.  And then I just work with the muscles, bones, and fascia. Or if we&rsquo;re working  with herbs or energy, I anticipate that the body wants to be in equilibrium and  then support it in ways that allow it to become so. It&rsquo;s like sculpting,  painting, or drawing. It&rsquo;s creative and intuitive. It&rsquo;s about letting something  emerge into what it naturally wants to be. </p>
<p>Healing is not something that&rsquo;s ownable.  It&rsquo;s a gift. It&rsquo;s spirit. It&rsquo;s you. You only can be a conduit for it. From a  Tlingit cosmology, it&rsquo;s very appropriate to share protocols and information on  how to live well and create good human beings.</p>
<figure>
    <img src="/images/blog/Gathering-in-Good-Medicine.jpg" alt="Twenty people seated in a circle in a museum gallery space, lined on one side with bright windows. In the center of their circle are rocks and pieces of wood, arranged like a fire pit." />
    <figcaption><div class="figcaption-inner">
            <em>Good Medicine</em> gathering with healers Martha Senungetuk and Anuqsraaq Mary Jane Litchard.  
            <div class="credit">
                Photo courtesy of the Anchorage Museum
            </div>
        </div></figcaption>
</figure>
<p><strong>I love what you&rsquo;ve  shared about the connection between healing and artmaking. I&rsquo;m wondering if you  could talk a little bit about curating <em>Good Medicine. </em>How was the  process of working with Indigenous healers within the bounds of cultural  protocols while simultaneously interfacing with the exhibitions team at the  Anchorage Museum? </strong></p>
<p>  I&rsquo;ve been  dedicated to this work for over twenty years now. I was born into it. It&rsquo;s a  hereditarily transmitted family occupation. If I were somebody who suddenly  decided to come in and talk about traditional healing, it would have met  extreme rebuke. It&rsquo;s a process. There are social checks and balances that occur  within Indigenous communities that look different in Western communities. </p>
<p>  I was able  to create <em>Good Medicine</em> because I&rsquo;ve earned the trust, respect, and support  of our Indigenous communities from around the state of Alaska. From there, it&rsquo;s  knowing the protocols and rules around what is acceptable in that space. There&rsquo;s  active medicine in that gallery, ceremony to protect and cleanse that space to  hold this content. </p>
<div class="image-left">
<figure>
    <img src="/images/blog/Mary-Jane-Litchard.jpg" alt="A woman, seated, wearing a blue patterned dress with embroidery, speaks into a microphone." />
    <figcaption><div class="figcaption-inner">
            Iñupiaq healer Anuqsraaq Mary Jane Litchard shares her practice.   
            <div class="credit">
                Photo courtesy of the Anchorage Museum
            </div>
        </div></figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p>  At first,  getting other healers to sign on to show their work was slow because, historically,  it hasn&rsquo;t been safe for Indigenous medicine people to be seen in a colonial  society. They were watching to see if it was going to come together and, if so,  how it would be received. We had success in opening the show, and invited  healers could see that we were doing it in a good way. So then other healers  felt safe to come in and be seen.</p>
<p>  Working with  the museum is another story. Obviously, concepts of time, intellectual property,  and priorities are not the same as Indigenous peoples or traditional healers. For  example, the museum wanted everything planned and scheduled months—even a year—in  advance. I couldn&rsquo;t get commitments from many healers that far ahead. But the museum  needs to make plans. </p>
<p>  I called in  people with whom I had longstanding relationships who could contribute certain  things, like <a href="https://www.instagram.com/haluxmarkings/" target="_blank">Dustin Newman Unignax̂</a>. We worked together to design the Medicine Wheel. Yéil  Yádi Olson worked with me to build the women&rsquo;s house,  and then he collaborated with Warren Jones on the design for the Yup&rsquo;ik men&rsquo;s  house.</p>
<p>  I felt like  an intermediary between two different sets of structures, priorities, and  values. The museum has been flexible in terms of shifting between what it wants  for a timeline and what it needs, which usually means enough time to freeze  materials for pest control or make appropriate mounts. The museum is also being  more relaxed about agendas for talks and events. Rather than having every  aspect planned out ahead of time, we let people show up and share whatever they  want to talk about. </p>
<p>  I think  overall, it&rsquo;s gone well, and there&rsquo;s been bending on both sides. <strong></strong></p>
<p><strong>Can you talk about how you prepared the  space to hold this knowledge? </strong></p>
<p>  Often, we  smudge (burn medicinal plants) to cleanse a space. But this space had to be  cleansed without burning things, due to fire-safety concerns. I ended up making  a blessed tea with stinkweed, rose, and tundra tea. I used a feather to spritz the  space with water and plant medicine. I put blessed sage, salt, and tobacco in  the four corners, to help shift the energy, bless the space, and alleviate  negativity. </p>
<p>  When we were  installing, I noticed museum employees coming up to sit and meditate in that  space. At a soul level, all people are Indigenous to a place at some point in  their ancestral line. All Indigenous people have medicine; however, there are  some groups that have been removed from it a little bit longer than Alaska  Native peoples have. It&rsquo;s an undeniable need that resonates in everybody&rsquo;s  heart and soul. There&rsquo;s a need for medicine and connectivity to the sacred. </p>
<p>  When we  opened the exhibition, we marked the space with ochre in a way that was  authentic, not performative. Admittedly, there was an aspect of rebellion in  that gesture. I ground the rock ochre and mixed it with egg whites. It&rsquo;s going  to be hard to get off the wall! It&rsquo;s not pretending to be medicine; it is medicine.  It was to say: this is my handprint. I reside in this space. </p>
<figure>
    <img src="/images/blog/anchorage-museum-handprint.jpg" alt="The negative of a handprint on a white wall, with brown paint splattered around it. Above, a brown arch with Y-shapes and dots radiating from it, as if growing out from the earth." />
    <figcaption><div class="figcaption-inner">
            One of the ochre paintings on the gallery walls. 
            <div class="credit">
                Photo courtesy of the Anchorage Museum
            </div>
        </div></figcaption>
</figure>
<p><strong>I think  people picked up on that, this positive energy of defiance you describe. You made  your mark on the wall, and then the cup of ochre was passed around, and other  people started spontaneously making different marks. Before you knew it, every wall  of the gallery was marked in some way.</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p>  I have a  video of Dustin from that night. He was grinning from ear to ear and said, &ldquo;I  feel like I&rsquo;m like two years old, and I&rsquo;m gonna get in so much trouble!&rdquo; We had  talked about incorporating pictographs or tattoo designs at one point but ended  up running out of time to weave them into the exhibition design. We both agreed  it was something that should be in the space. It happened so spontaneously when  he had the ochre. He started using his hands to paint those shapes.</p>
<p>  Authentic  play and joy—that is medicine.</p>
<p><strong>What do you hope  that Native and non-Native communities and audience members take away from this  exhibition? </strong><strong></strong></p>
<p>  I&rsquo;m not sure  what non-Native people will take away. I think it would be good if there was an  understanding of this history of colonization—also, a desire to be good allies  and to support healing, to recognize and perpetuate the understanding that we&rsquo;re  not extinct, that we&rsquo;re alive and well, practicing our traditions.  Understanding the harm done is important so that we don&rsquo;t perpetuate or inflict  future harm. </p>
<p>  Often,  museums talk about Indigenous cultures in the past tense, showing culture that&rsquo;s  not being lived. Once culture is not actively engaged in, it transitions into a  dying culture. Being in the museum and being able to co-create this space with  other healers where people are showing recent work and actively blessing and  marking the space—it&rsquo;s very progressive. Marking the space with egg whites and  ochre was a gesture of ownership—not to irritate the museum but to have a  stance of autonomy and sovereignty and active participation in culture. <em>This  is our space, and we&rsquo;re practicing medicine here</em>. It&rsquo;s a bit forward to do  that, but I&rsquo;m responsible for holding that space and making it safe for other  people. These are the steps that are needed to be taken to do that.&nbsp; </p>
<p><strong>Do you  see museums as potential sites for healing? And what does that look like to  you?</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong></strong></p>
<p>  Yes, of  course I do. Museums have played a part in removing culture from communities in  the past. Cultural belongings were collected in the name of Western academia. I  was just at a traditional  potlatch memorial party, and we had  over twenty objects repatriated from a museum. One item was a hat that had been  taken from a Tlingit family by the police. This hat later found its way into a  museum collection under dubious circumstances. Not long ago, during the Jim  Crow era, practicing our culture and spirituality was illegal and was punished accordingly.</p>
<p>  We are in  this in-between space now where people should not need to be legitimized by  museums. It&rsquo;s not a museum&rsquo;s place to legitimize our access to culture;  however, it is a museum&rsquo;s place to assist in that reclamation of culture. Because  museums are institutions of power, part of the reconciliation process is  leveraging that privilege and power for the healing and betterment of the local  Indigenous peoples.</p>
<p class="top-40"><em>Francesca Du Brock is the chief curator at the Anchorage Museum, a <a href="https://affiliations.si.edu/" target="_blank">Smithsonian Affiliate</a>. Her  curatorial practice is informed by her background as an artist and educator and  is grounded in social engagement, place-based storytelling, and environmental  justice. She holds an MFA from  the San Francisco Arts Institute and an EdM from Harvard&rsquo;s Graduate School of  Education.</em></p>
<p><em>Meda Dewitt is a Tlingit (Lingít) traditional healer,  certified massage therapist, ethnoherbalist, educator, and events coordinator. She has a master&rsquo;s degree of arts in Alaska Native traditional healing from  the Alaska Pacific University, and she is currently in an Indigenous studies  doctoral program at Te Whare Wananga o Awanuiarangi, New Zealand.</em></p>
    <div class="disqus top-40">
